post_text:
Letterjacket orders re-scheduled

A representative from BSN will be at the high school on Tuesday, September 22, at 9am for students wanting to order a letter jackets. BSN requires a $200 cash or money order deposit payment so that the jacket order can be placed.

They do not accept personal checks. If students want to order but forget to bring the down payment with them, BSN will still take measurements and make notes for the order, but everyone must bring a payment to the school before the order is placed.

BSN will drop by at a later date to pick up payments made after September 22.

An order form and sizing chart can be picked up off the ledge at the front office window.

Any questions can be referred to 918-618-2022.

post_text:
IMPORTANT: Notice About Schedule Changes

Mrs. Westfall will be conducting all high school schedule changes via telephone conference. Students who need to request schedule changes need to email Mrs. Westfall to schedule a telephone conference. We will adhere to dates previously posted.

JUNIORS & SENIORS – Monday, August 10
FRESHMEN & SOPHOMORES – Monday, August 17

Please email Mrs. Westfall (bwestfall@heavenerschools.org) by the morning of the date set aside for your grade level. Include in your email a description of changes you need and a telephone number where you can be reached. Mrs. Westfall will contact you via telephone between 8:30 a.m. and 3:00 p.m. on the day reserved for your grade.
Students who do not complete requests according to dates posted will have to wait until school begins to complete schedule changes.

post_text:
From your HS Counselor:
Students who are taking concurrent classes, remember that CASC classes begin August 12, so even though high school classes are not in session until August 20, you must log in to your CASC classes and begin work to maintain your enrollment.

Enrollment is still open, so if you have qualifying test scores and GPA, and if you are on target with high school credits, you can still apply for concurrent enrollment. For incoming seniors who did not get to take the ACT, CASC is making exceptions by considering your GPA. Remember that students must pay the fees for each online class. Tuition is free for concurrent students, but fees run close to $300 per online class. Students with CDIB may qualify for assistance with fees. Contact the Choctaw Nation for details.

Online courses fill up fast, so please don't delay if concurrent enrollment is something you need. To download and print an application packet for concurrent enrollment, go to https://www.carlalbert.edu/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Concurrent-Enrollment-Application-Packet-for-New-Students.pdf

post_text:
From HS Counselors
Oklahoma college tuition and fees can cost students from $5000 to $15000 per year. Although many high school students currently do not have college plans on their radars, many change their minds by the end of the senior year. That's why it's important to apply for Oklahoma's Promise. Students have until the end of the sophomore year, and this year, Oklahoma's Promise is offering estimated income for those whose adjusted gross income will be impacted this year due to employment changes caused by COVID-19 restrictions. The deadline to take advantage of this opportunity is June 30, 2020. Please do not pass up this opportunity. For more information, see https://secure.okcollegestart.org/applications/oklahoma_promise/apply.html?fbclid=IwAR0kFQxf-98sNNq3zYpQ0G653kZ0NtFVMmc9eg6jYGtJqlowoCE63ZORM_w

post_text: From HS Counselors: Students who will be grades 9-12 beginning August 2020 should check school email. Any student who received an emailed course request form this week did not complete/submit forms that were emailed several weeks ago, or the submission did not go through. Please make sure you complete these forms by June 15. Course requests are used to create student schedules in July when the master schedule is finalized. If you did not receive an email, it is because you already submitted your form in April. Students who have problems completing forms should email bwestfall@heavenerschools.org. Thank you.

post_text:
From HS Teacher, Mrs. Martin:
Friday, May 8th, we will have the Seniors' final drive. We will gather at CV's parking lot at 7:45 PM (please park close to the highway so as to leave the store room for parking) and leave promptly at 8:00 PM. Stay in your vehicles ... observe social distancing rules. We will drive south on the highway to Hwy 128 and turn left. We will then make our way east on Ave I behind and around Harvey Stadium where the lights will be on in your honor. We will turn left on Ave G and drive in front of the high school and elementary school at which time the drive will be over. There will be no gatherings at the school.

Officer Puckett will lead the drive and other officers will be monitoring the drive. Any reckless driving or burnouts will be ticketed by the police. We want a safe drive, so help us out.

From High School Counselors: You’ve likely seen news reports of teacher parades driving by homes of students to wave and shout out words of encouragement. This is just one example that shows what students mean to the people who devote their careers to educating children.

Educators at Heavener High School are no different, but rather than organizing a parade, HHS teachers and counselors got together to create their own shout-outs from the safety of their homes.

Students of Heavener High School, this video is for you. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SSVkIAceXjY&feature=youtu.be

post_text: PSA...The Oklahoma Educational Television Authority (OETA) is collaborating with the OSDE to provide in-home learning opportunities for students while schools are closed due to coronavirus. Beginning today, March 30, OETA will be adjusting its daytime schedule to provide curriculum-based programming for students Monday-Friday from 6am until 6pm, which will last until the end of the school year. Please visit http://www.oeta.tv/LearningAtHome to view an updated program schedule, OETA’s statewide channel list, curriculum and activities.

From HHS Counselors: Choctaw Career Services will be on the high school campus on Tuesday, March 10, to speak with high school seniors who are members of the Choctaw Nation. Career Services helps adult students pay for education and/or training leading to a license or certificate (and this funding is not dependent on income), so this is an incredible opportunity for students needing assistance with funding their post secondary education or training.
The meeting will be held in the high school library from 9:00 - 10:50.

From HHS Counselors: The Oklahoma State Fair Scholarship deadline is March 20, 2020.
ELIGIBILITY CRITERIA
In order to be eligible to compete for one of the Oklahoma State Fair, Inc. scholarships, applicants must meet
the following criteria:
- Current year high school graduate of an accredited high school or homeschool located in Oklahoma
- Enrolling in a college, university, vocational or technical school in the state of Oklahoma.
- Legal resident of Oklahoma.
- United States citizen.
- Upload all supporting documents to the online application at the time of submission.
https://okstatefair.com/osf-gives-back/scholarships

From your HHS Counselors: How about a chance to win $30,000 to go toward your college education by doodling? That's right. The winner of this competition also earns his or her school $50,000 to set up a computer lab.

The Doodle for Google Scholarship is open to students grades K-12 and encourages students "to use their creativity to create their own interpretation of the Google logo."

This year's theme is "I show kindness by..."

For information on how the scholarship contest works, how to enter, and specific contest rules, go to https://doodles.google.com/d4g/how-it-works/

From HHS Couselors: Did you know there are organizations that offer scholarships to populations with specific disabilities?
The Joseph James Morelli Legacy Foundation awards scholarships to students with documented diagnosis of dyslexia, dysgraphia, or dyscalculia.
The Organization for Autism Research offers scholarships for students with an autism diagnosis.
The Lighthouse Guild offers scholarships to students with vision loss.
For details about these scholarships and more, see our scholarship page at https://www.heavenerschools.org/2019-20-scholarships
